05066nam a22005655i 9780226819105DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226819105  a(DE-B1597)618912  a(OCoLC)1302012632  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aSB482 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a363.6/809731 aJarvis, Jonathan B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNational Parks Forever :bFifty Years of Fighting and a Case for Independence /cJonathan B. Jarvis, T. Destry Jarvis. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b20 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction and a Brief History of the National Parks: 1872– 1972 -- tOne. Growing the System and Telling a More Complete Story -- tTwo. Alaska: Doing It Right the First Time -- tThree. The Politics of Park Policy -- tFour. Using the Best Available Science -- tFive. Ecosystem Thinking Requires Collaboration -- tSix. Interference in the Mission -- tSeven. Independence: Finding a Sustainable Future for a Perpetuity Agency -- tNotes -- tBibliography and Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo leaders of the National Park Service provide a front-row seat to the disastrous impact of partisan politics over the past fifty years—and offer a bold vision for the parks’ future. The US National Parks, what environmentalist and historian Wallace Stegner called America’s “best idea,” are under siege. Since 1972, partisan political appointees in the Department of the Interior have offered two conflicting views of the National Park Service (NPS): one vision emphasizes preservation and science-based decision-making, and another prioritizes economic benefits and privatization. These politically driven shifts represent a pernicious, existential threat to the very future of our parks. For the past fifty years, brothers Jonathan B. and T. Destry Jarvis have worked both within and outside NPS as leaders and advocates. National Parks Forever interweaves their two voices to show how our parks must be protected from those who would open them to economic exploitation, while still allowing generations to explore and learn in them. Their history also details how Congress and administration appointees have used budget and staffing cuts to sabotage NPS’s ability to manage the parks and even threatened their existence. Drawing on their experience, Jarvis and Jarvis make a bold and compelling proposal: that it is time for NPS to be removed from the Department of the Interior and made an independent agency, similar to the Smithsonian Institution, giving NPS leaders the ability to manage park resources and plan our parks’ protection, priorities, and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConservation of natural resourcesxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aConservation of natural resources-Government policy-United States. 0aNational parks and reserveszUnited States. 0aNational parks and reserves-United States-History. 0aNational parks and reserves-United States. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  anational park service, nps, parks, conservation, conservationism, environment, environmentalism, environmentalists, independence, politics, political opinions, partisanship, united states of america, usa, american society, history, historical context, budget, resource management, government, governmental policy, reserves, alaska, science, ecosystem, collaboration, leadership, sustainable future, protection, threats, proposal, changes.1 aJarvis, T. Destry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJohns, C